TY  - JOUR
T1  - Can capital movements eliminate the need for technology transfer?
AU  - McCulloch, Rachel
AU  - Yellen, Janet
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 12
IS  - 1
SP  - 95
EP  - 106
PY  - 1982
DA  - 1982/02/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(82)90077-0
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199682900770
AB  - This paper analyzes the welfare and efficiency implications of barriers to international transfer of technology. We show that the consequences of such barriers depend critically upon the extent of international capital mobility. When capital is perfectly mobile, policies that impede technology transfer may have no effect on employment, income distribution, or national welfare, despite one country's clear technological superiority in an industry. This conclusion holds even if there is a rigid wage and resulting unemployment in one country.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Capital movement as a substitute for technology transfer: A comment
AU  - Chipman, John S.
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 12
IS  - 1
SP  - 107
EP  - 109
PY  - 1982
DA  - 1982/02/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(82)90078-2
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199682900782
AB  - A simple proof using duality theory is furnished of some results of McCulloch and Yellen (1982) relating to a two-commodity, two-factor, two-country model with identical technologies in one industry. If the developed country has uniformly superior technology (hence uniformly lower unit costs at each set of factor rentals) in the other industry, with international capital mobility the less developed country will specialize in the good produced with the identical technology; nevertheless wages as well as rentals of capital will be equalized. The same techniques are used to extend the proposition to the case of wage rigidity and unemployment.
ER  - 

