EP  - 141
PY  - 1982
DA  - 1982/02/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(82)90080-0
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199682900800
AB  - When labor is imperfectly mobile between industries, workers may have a special interest in commercial policies that increase the price of the output of the industry in which they are employed. This proposition is investigated in a two-good model in which the ‘degree of labor mobility’ is measured by the elasticity of a convex input transformation curve. The existence of such a transformation curve is justified by a model in which individual workers have differing relative and absolute efficiencies in different industries. The results are extended to the case of many industries.
ER  - 

