IS  - 1
SP  - 143
EP  - 163
PY  - 1982
DA  - 1982/02/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(82)90081-2
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199682900812
AB  - A small country faces uncertainty about the world price of a good and wishes to impose a ceiling on (1) the expected foreign exchange expenditure on imports and (2) the expected volume of imports — using either a quota on foreign exchange expenditure or a quota on the volume of imports. The expenditure quota yields higher expected consumer's surplus if the demand elasticity is high; the reverse tends to be true if the demand elasticity is low. The introduction of an upward slope in the random supply curve tends to increase (decrease) the break-even value of the demand elasticity if the uncertainty in the inverse supply curve is additive (multiplicative).
