AB  - Two-gap and related theoretical models imply that different constraints on growth may be binding at different times. This paper develops and applies an econometric methodology suitable for estimating this type of model and determining which constraints hold at different times. The empirical results suggest that growth is more often constrained by savings than by foreign exchange and that these models can be used to interpret the behavior of LDCs during the oil crisis.
